      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are the three basic rules of double-entry bookkeeping?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The three traditional rules are debit the receiver and credit the giver for personal accounts, debit what comes in and credit what goes out for real accounts, and debit all expenses and losses while crediting all incomes and gains for nominal accounts. Buying furniture for Rs 50,000 in cash debits Furniture, a real account, and credits Cash, so the trial balance stays equal."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between single-entry and double-entry bookkeeping?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Single entry records only one side of a transaction, usually cash and personal accounts, while double entry records an equal debit and credit for every transaction so the books self-balance. Single entry cannot produce a reliable trial balance, balance sheet or audit trail. Double entry is what allows profit to be proved twice, through the profit and loss account and through the movement in capital."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is double-entry bookkeeping compulsory for companies in India?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, Section 128(1) of the Companies Act 2013 requires every company to keep books of account on the accrual basis and according to the double entry system. Since 1 April 2023 those books must also be maintained in software with an audit trail that records every edit and cannot be disabled, which effectively rules out spreadsheet-only ledgers for companies."
          }
        }
